The 'bee car' that avoids collisions
In order to move forward in the development of technologies for the prevention of accidents, Nissan has been inspired, this time, by nature, in particular, by bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, based on the flying of bees, avoids accidents.
This is the Bio-mimic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C which is the first step in collision prevention technologies.
The engineers of the Nissan Motor Advanced Technical Centre Co. have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Centre for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Development of Brand Management, the BR23C is presented as an extension of the Security Shield from four areas of Nissan.
This robot intends to strengthen the collision prevention capacity of the brand's vehicles.
During their flight, each bee creates its own personal, oval-shaped space that looks a lot like the Nissan Security Shield.
But the most important thing is the composite eyes of the bee, able to see with an angle of more than 300 degrees in all directions, which allows it to fly without interruption within its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, the engineers designed what they called a laser locator (Laser Range Finder).
It detects obstacles that are up to two meters away within a 180-degree radius in front of BR23C, calculates the distance to that object and sends a signal to an abort microprocessor that immediately results in collision prevention.
"When you detect an obstacle, the small robot will imitate the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by turning its wheels at a right or greater angle to avoid collision.
The biggest difference with any existing system is that the escape maneuver is totally instinctive.
If not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles, "explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and main engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be diverted up or down, or diagonal; it can only be moved in two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to turn its wheels and not in infinite directions and ways like bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, to prevent collisions by the small robot.
"This device only needs to process information every few seconds, and act according to that data.
It does not require to save information or intuitive logic from previous maneuvers, so it can work continuously with just a couple dozen KB memory.
This may be a surprise, but we're not talking about memory gigas, not even mega. "
This is the first step to develop new technologies for instant collision prevention, a technology that Nissan vaticina will be introduced into serial cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than the variety of lithium ions.
Another possible future application of this technology could be the integration of the unit with a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to its destination by avoiding obstacles along the way.
