Rafael Correa in Quito, this Monday.
Refounded the republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the common project of the Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, the Boliviano Evo Morales and the Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, as an example of his colleagues and friends, is the third to vote on a draft for a new Constitution.
Mission accomplished as 64 per cent of the voters voted "yes" to the referendum, according to the official results of 80 per cent of the votes.
According to these results, "no" received 28%, 7% of the votes were invalid and 0.7% were blank votes.
For the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to obtain half of the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls on the way out of the electoral centres and a count by a non-governmental organization had announced a wide victory of "yes," estimated at 63 to 70 per cent.
Rafael Correa had also claimed on the night of Sunday to Monday the victory of his draft Constitution.
The "Constitution triumphed in an overwhelming way," he had assured, congratulating the Ecuadorians who lead the government of Guayaquil, 280 kilometres south-west of Quito.
Thus, Rafael Correa has been congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also by his Chilean colleague Micaela Bachelet.
The elections, which will take place in full calm, according to the observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), referred to a text of 444 points that consolidated the "new socialism" defended by the President.
The draft Constitution implies an increase in the State's power over the economy, reserving it the "development planning" of a country that lives essentially through the extraction of oil by foreign companies and through foreign exchange that send its emigrants.
The project, led by Correa, elected in 2006, also grants strengthened powers to the head of State, who will be able to make up to two consecutive terms of four years each and will have the possibility to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa already announced that he would use this power and seek a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution further consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the President began to establish in this country of 13.9 million people, in which 50 per cent of the population lives below the poverty line.
It finally provides for the interdiction of the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for American drug operations.
The 19 people abducted have been released in Chad
An Egyptian command launched the assault on the kidnappers of the 11 tourists and their eight captives captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions abducted ten days ago in the desert arrived unharmed in the Egyptian capital after being released on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they had been released by Egyptian special forces in Chad.
They all looked good on their arrival at 15H30 on board a special aircraft to the Al Maza military base, adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
Helicopters immediately transported them to the Maadi hospital, a residential suburb of Cairo, for medical testing, so they have been unable to speak to the press.
"They are well in health" and "no ransom was paid" to the kidnappers, Egyptian tourism minister Zohear Garana said at the airport.
On 19 September, these hostages fell into the hands of 35 unknown kidnappers while enjoying a safari in the SUV in a desert area at the foot of Mount Ouanat, in the confines of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, and have since passed from one zulo to another.
The group consisted of 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - and eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, one border guard and the director of the Aegyptous travel agency, in charge of the safari organization.
An Egyptian security officer indicated that 30 special forces, carried on board two helicopters, had launched the assault during the night before dawn.
"An exchange of shots took place, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others have fled," said this responsible who kept the anonymous.
According to him, 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "lightning" unit were sent to Sudan, where they were supported by German and Italian commanders.
The Italian Foreign Minister, Franco Frattini, mentioned in Belgrade the role played by the secret agents and members of the Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and effectiveness of our men in the secret services, the special forces," he said without going into details.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
On the eve of the day, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted during a patrol an SUV on board which the kidnappers were found, of which six were killed, including the Chadian chief and two were arrested.
He also stated that they were related to a rebel group in Darfur, the Sudan-Unity Liberation Movement (SLA-U), a statement immediately rejected by that group.
