European Union doubles its trade with India
As the European Union and India are mutually trading partners, this issue, in addition to the other problems for the most part global, dominated the agenda of the ninth summit.
Today, too, a Franco-Indian summit will be held to deal mainly with cooperation in nuclear energy.
While the European Union recognizes that India is a great democratic developing power that should have more voice and vote in international affairs, member countries have not yet been able to reach a common denominator on whether they should support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
This issue has not been addressed at the ninth summit in Marseilles yesterday.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, President of the EU, José Manuel Barroso, President of the Commission and Javier Solana, the main representative of foreign policy, received Manmohan Singh, Prime Minister of India, with whom they agreed to double in five years, that is to increase their trade to more than 100 billion euros.
In view of the fact that between 2000 and 2007 the exchange of goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this is not an overly ambitious objective.
They thus legally harmonized the existing twenty-six bilateral civil aviation conventions with India, so that air transport will also be able to fly in the future.
India wants to sign the free trade treaty with the Union until the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the negotiations.
The objective is balance, because while the EU is India's first trading partner, New Delhi is only ninth among the Union's trading partners.
The summit paid attention to global issues.
Both sides condemned the Afghan and Pakistani situation and terrorism - all forms of it - and urged the convening of a UN conference.
The conclusion of the Doha round of trade liberalization was also called for, although both sides have a strong responsibility for their failure.
The EU confirmed that it will hold on to its energy and climate programme, that is, by 2020 it wants to reduce pollutant emissions by at least 20%.
India also agrees with this, as at next year's climate conference, a global agreement should be reached and the production of greenhouse gases should be reduced by 50 per cent by 2050.
They also wished to hinder the rise in food prices and supported the convening of an international conference to review the financial crisis.
Today, the head of government of India will travel to the French capital, where - in a bilateral meeting - he will sign an agreement on the peaceful use of nuclear energy.
Paris is confident that French companies will receive orders worth EUR 20 billion to build nuclear reactors.
According to news agency reports the agreement would be for a period of 15 years.
